# Comprehensive Research: Airbnb Founders - Brian Chesky, Joe Gebbia, and Nathan Blecharczyk

## Overview

Airbnb was founded in 2008 by three entrepreneurs who transformed a simple idea born out of financial necessity into a global hospitality platform valued at over $100 billion. The three co-founders each brought unique backgrounds and skills that proved complementary in building one of the most successful startups of the 21st century.

## Brian Chesky - Co-founder and CEO

### Background and Early Life
Brian Joseph Chesky was born on August 29, 1981, in Niskayuna, New York. His parents are Robert H. Chesky and Deborah Chesky; they both were social workers. His father is of Polish ancestry, whereas his mother is of Italian descent. When Chesky was a child, he was interested in art, drawing, and design, and he often redesigned shoes and toys. Later, his interests shifted to landscape architecture and design.

### Education and Early Career
In 1999, Brian Chesky enrolled at the Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) and served as their hockey team captain. He completed his RISD program in 2004 and was awarded a Bachelor of Fine Arts in industrial design. While at RISD, Chesky met Joe Gebbia, who would later become his best friend, housemate, and one of Airbnb's co-founders.

In his early 20s, he also became a competitive bodybuilder, and a 2014 profile said he still had "16-inch biceps." After completing his RISD program, Brian Chesky relocated to Los Angeles. Subsequently, he found an industrial designer job that fetched $40,000 annually.

At age 22 he was overcome by a "weird feeling of mortality." A sense of "this is my life": Commuting in LA traffic alone to a job in a design company. It was a let down after he'd started to believe the high-minded rhetoric from Rhode Island School of Design that designers could "design the world around them." He quit that job, rolled up a foam bed into his crappy Honda Civic and moved in with his old design pal Joe Gebbia in San Francisco.

### Founding Airbnb
In October 2007, he moved to San Francisco to live with RISD classmate Joe Gebbia. Chesky did not have enough money to pay his rent, and they opened their house to short-term renters as a bed and breakfast, providing air mattresses for guests to sleep on and Pop-Tarts for breakfast during the Industrial Designers Society of America conference, when hotel rooms were scarce. The business became Airbnb.

### Leadership Style and Philosophy
Brian Chesky is the co-founder and Chief Executive Officer of Airbnb and sets the vision and strategy for the company. A graduate from the Rhode Island School of Design, Brian has embedded his creative roots in Airbnb's culture, product and community. This design-driven approach has enabled a system of trust that allows strangers to live together, and created a unique business model that facilitates connection and belonging.

In September 2024, Chesky gave a 2-hour talk at a Y Combinator event on his leadership style, later coined "founder mode" by American computer scientist Paul Graham in an essay. Chesky's talk garnered attention quickly and became the subject of widespread discussion and memes.

### Current Status and Philanthropy
As of May 2023, Airbnb's market capitalization is $74.9 billion, and its 42-year-old CEO has a real-time net worth estimated at $9.3 billion. On June 11, 2016, Chesky joined Warren Buffett and Bill Gates' The Giving Pledge, a group of billionaires who have committed to giving the majority of their wealth away.

## Joe Gebbia - Co-founder

### Background and Early Life
Gebbia was born August 21, 1981, in Atlanta, Georgia, the son of Eileen and Joe Gebbia, independent health food sales representatives. Gebbia is of Italian and Irish ancestry. He grew up in Lawrenceville, Georgia and has one sister, Kimberly. Gebbia attended Brookwood High School in Snellville, Georgia.

### Education and Artistic Background
Joe began his life as an artist and graduated from the Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) where he earned dual degrees in Graphic Design and Industrial Design, and currently serves on the RISD Board of Trustees. Most people don't know that Joe began his life as an artist eventually double majoring in graphic design and industrial design.

### Role in Founding Airbnb
In 2007, Brian Chesky, his classmate at RISD, moved in with him, and they both quit their jobs to start a company together. Gebbia came up with the idea of renting out airbeds in their apartment. As a result, Gebbia wrote Chesky with an idea: What if they turned their loft into a designer's bed and breakfast, with a sleeping mat and breakfast included? They opted to welcome some conference attendees in their room right away as a way of "making some bucks." They bought three airbeds and hosted three guests, effectively initiating the bed and breakfast business.

### Career Evolution and Current Roles
In July 2022, Gebbia stepped down from his full-time operating role at Airbnb, while remaining on the board of directors in an advisory role. In September 2022, Gebbia was appointed by Tesla, Inc. to its board of directors.

Samara, formerly a research and development unit of Airbnb established in 2016, became an independent accessory dwelling unit (ADU) startup in 2022. Gebbia announced the launch of its first product in November 2022, a net-zero tiny house called Backyard.

### Recent Political Role
In 2025, he joined the Department of Government Efficiency (DOGE). Gebbia was appointed by President Donald Trump as the first Chief Design Officer to lead the National Design Studio.

### Philanthropy
In December 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic, Gebbia made a $25 million donation to benefit two San Francisco charities working to end homelessness in the San Francisco Bay Area: Rising UpLarkin Street Youth Services and All Home. In May 2022, while Gebbia was the graduation speaker at his alma mater, Brookwood High School, he pledged 22 shares of Airbnb stock to each of the 890 graduates, a gift worth a total of $2.1 million.

## Nathan Blecharczyk - Co-founder and Chief Strategy Officer

### Background and Early Life
Blecharczyk was born in 1983, the son of Sheila (ne Underwood) and Paul Steven Blecharczyk, who is Polish-American. His ancestors came to the United States around the time of World War I. He grew up in an upper-middle-class family in Boston, Massachusetts. He attended Boston Latin Academy, graduating in 2001.

### Early Entrepreneurship
During high school, he made money by creating a software business. His web-hosting business provided services to spammers and was once listed on The Spamhaus Project "Registry of Known Spam Operators (ROKSO)" which lists the top spamming services.

Lifelong entrepreneur, Nathan Blecharczyk started coding at the age of 12. At the age of 14, his first customer paid $1000 for his work he saw online. By the time he finished high school, he made over $1 million.

Blecharczyk, a then 19-year-old self-taught engineer, already raked in $1 million from the software business he developed in high school. From as young as 14, he started attracting clients from all over the world who sought his help in writing computer programs.

### Education and Career Development
But by the second year, it was becoming too much to try to balance that," Blecharczyk told FOX Business. Drawing on the confidence that his father instilled in him at a very young age, he shut down his business knowing "that there would be other opportunities in the future."

In 2005, he graduated with a bachelor's degree in computer science, which helped him not only build the technological underpinnings for Airbnb but negotiate with policymakers in communities around the world to enable the company's expansion.

### Role in Founding Airbnb
In February 2008, Nathan Blecharczyk, Chesky's former roommate, joined as the chief technology officer and the third co-founder of the new venture, which they named "AirBed & Breakfast". In 2008, Blecharczyk partnered with Brian Chesky and Joe Gebbia to found Airbnb, and was the company's first chief technology officer and coded the company's original website using Ruby on Rails.

### Current Role and Responsibilities
Nathan (Nate) Blecharczyk is the co-founder of Airbnb and Chief Strategy Officer. Nate plays a leading role in driving key strategic initiatives across the global business, particularly those which require a holistic understanding of the business, public policy, product, data, and Airbnb's long-term stakeholder interests. Nate has led the creation of Airbnb's engineering, data science, payments, and performance marketing teams.

In his role as chief strategy officer, Blecharczyk is in charge of making nice with local governments within the U.S. and around the world and convincing landlords to let the tenants rent their rooms on Airbnb. "I take a very long-term view that it's important to have positive relations with regulators and create value for the stakeholders," he says.

### Personal Life and Net Worth
Blecharczyk is the 203rd richest person in the world according to Forbes, with a net worth of $9.4 billion, mostly due to his ownership of 62 million shares of Airbnb. Blecharczyk resides in San Francisco, California. He is married to Elizabeth Morey Blecharczyk, a neonatologist. They have two children; Blecharczyk has been a supporter of parental leave for fathers.

Blecharczyk joined Warren Buffett and Bill Gates' 'The Giving Pledge', a select group of billionaires who have committed to give the majority of their wealth away.

## The Early Struggle and Creative Solutions

### The Cereal Box Innovation
During their early struggles to secure funding, the founders demonstrated remarkable creativity and perseverance. Later that year, after failing to raise funding, the founders bought mass quantities of cereal, designed packaging branded as '"Obama O's" and "Cap'n McCain's" cereal to sell at the Democratic National Convention in Denver, Colorado. Originally intended as a marketing ploy, the company sold enough cereal to raise $30,000, and attracted the attention of Paul Graham, who invited the founders to the January 2009 winter training session of his startup incubator, Y Combinator, which provided them with training and $20,000 in funding in exchange for a 6% interest in the company.

### Y Combinator and Growth
In early 2009, Chesky, Gebbia, and Blecharczyk enrolled in a Y Combinator startup course. The course provided US$20,000 in seed money and training from Paul Graham, among others, in exchange for a six-percent stake in the company. Sequoia Capital partner Greg McAdoo invested US$585,000 in what was now known as Airbnb at the end of the course.

## Company Evolution and Success

In December 2020, Airbnb became a public company via an initial public offering. Since then, Brian has overseen Airbnb's growth to become a community of over 5 million hosts who have welcomed more than 2 billion guests across 240+ countries and regions.

The three founders represent a unique combination of design thinking (Chesky and Gebbia from RISD) and technical expertise (Blecharczyk from Harvard), which proved essential in creating both a user-friendly platform and the underlying technology infrastructure. Their story demonstrates how complementary skills, creative problem-solving during difficult times, and long-term vision can transform a simple idea into a global business phenomenon.

---

**Sources:**
- Airbnb official newsroom and investor relations pages
- Wikipedia entries for all three founders
- Business publications including CNBC, Fox Business, Medium
- Interviews and profiles from various entrepreneurship publications

In early 2009, Chesky, Gebbia, and Blecharczyk enrolled in a Y Combinator startup course. The course provided US$20,000 in seed money and training from Paul Graham, among others, in exchange for a six-percent stake in the company. Sequoia Capital partner Greg McAdoo invested US$585,000 in what was now known as Airbnb at the end of the course.

## Company Evolution and Success

In December 2020, Airbnb became a public company via an initial public offering. Since then, Brian has overseen Airbnb's growth to become a community of over 5 million hosts who have welcomed more than 2 billion guests across 240+ countries and regions.

The three founders represent a unique combination of design thinking (Chesky and Gebbia from RISD) and technical expertise (Blecharczyk from Harvard), which proved essential in creating both a user-friendly platform and the underlying technology infrastructure. Their story demonstrates how complementary skills, creative problem-solving during difficult times, and long-term vision can transform a simple idea into a global business phenomenon.

---

- Airbnb official newsroom and investor relations pages

- Business publications including CNBC, Fox Business, Medium
- Interviews and profiles from various entrepreneurship publications

# Comprehensive Research: Airbnb Founders - Brian Chesky, Joe Gebbia, and Nathan Blecharczyk

## Overview

Airbnb was founded in 2008 by three entrepreneurs who transformed a simple idea born out of financial necessity into a global hospitality platform valued at over $100 billion. The three co-founders each brought unique backgrounds and skills that proved complementary in building one of the most successful startups of the 21st century.

## Brian Chesky - Co-founder and CEO

### Background and Early Life
Brian Joseph Chesky was born on August 29, 1981, in Niskayuna, New York. His parents are Robert H. Chesky and Deborah Chesky; they both were social workers. His father is of Polish ancestry, whereas his mother is of Italian descent. When Chesky was a child, he was interested in art, drawing, and design, and he often redesigned shoes and toys. Later, his interests shifted to landscape architecture and design.

### Education and Early Career
In 1999, Brian Chesky enrolled at the Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) and served as their hockey team captain. He completed his RISD program in 2004 and was awarded a Bachelor of Fine Arts in industrial design. While at RISD, Chesky met Joe Gebbia, who would later become his best friend, housemate, and one of Airbnb's co-founders.

In his early 20s, he also became a competitive bodybuilder, and a 2014 profile said he still had "16-inch biceps." After completing his RISD program, Brian Chesky relocated to Los Angeles. Subsequently, he found an industrial designer job that fetched $40,000 annually.

At age 22 he was overcome by a "weird feeling of mortality." A sense of "this is my life": Commuting in LA traffic alone to a job in a design company. It was a let down after he'd started to believe the high-minded rhetoric from Rhode Island School of Design that designers could "design the world around them." He quit that job, rolled up a foam bed into his crappy Honda Civic and moved in with his old design pal Joe Gebbia in San Francisco.

### Founding Airbnb
In October 2007, he moved to San Francisco to live with RISD classmate Joe Gebbia. Chesky did not have enough money to pay his rent, and they opened their house to short-term renters as a bed and breakfast, providing air mattresses for guests to sleep on and Pop-Tarts for breakfast during the Industrial Designers Society of America conference, when hotel rooms were scarce. The business became Airbnb.

### Leadership Style and Philosophy
Brian Chesky is the co-founder and Chief Executive Officer of Airbnb and sets the vision and strategy for the company. A graduate from the Rhode Island School of Design, Brian has embedded his creative roots in Airbnb's culture, product and community. This design-driven approach has enabled a system of trust that allows strangers to live together, and created a unique business model that facilitates connection and belonging.

In September 2024, Chesky gave a 2-hour talk at a Y Combinator event on his leadership style, later coined "founder mode" by American computer scientist Paul Graham in an essay. Chesky's talk garnered attention quickly and became the subject of widespread discussion and memes.

### Current Status and Philanthropy
As of May 2023, Airbnb's market capitalization is $74.9 billion, and its 42-year-old CEO has a real-time net worth estimated at $9.3 billion. On June 11, 2016, Chesky joined Warren Buffett and Bill Gates' The Giving Pledge, a group of billionaires who have committed to giving the majority of their wealth away.

## Joe Gebbia - Co-founder

### Background and Early Life
Gebbia was born August 21, 1981, in Atlanta, Georgia, the son of Eileen and Joe Gebbia, independent health food sales representatives. Gebbia is of Italian and Irish ancestry. He grew up in Lawrenceville, Georgia and has one sister, Kimberly. Gebbia attended Brookwood High School in Snellville, Georgia.

### Education and Artistic Background
Joe began his life as an artist and graduated from the Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) where he earned dual degrees in Graphic Design and Industrial Design, and currently serves on the RISD Board of Trustees. Most people don't know that Joe began his life as an artist eventually double majoring in graphic design and industrial design.

### Role in Founding Airbnb
In 2007, Brian Chesky, his classmate at RISD, moved in with him, and they both quit their jobs to start a company together. Gebbia came up with the idea of renting out airbeds in their apartment. As a result, Gebbia wrote Chesky with an idea: What if they turned their loft into a designer's bed and breakfast, with a sleeping mat and breakfast included? They opted to welcome some conference attendees in their room right away as a way of "making some bucks." They bought three airbeds and hosted three guests, effectively initiating the bed and breakfast business.

### Career Evolution and Current Roles
In July 2022, Gebbia stepped down from his full-time operating role at Airbnb, while remaining on the board of directors in an advisory role. In September 2022, Gebbia was appointed by Tesla, Inc. to its board of directors.

Samara, formerly a research and development unit of Airbnb established in 2016, became an independent accessory dwelling unit (ADU) startup in 2022. Gebbia announced the launch of its first product in November 2022, a net-zero tiny house called Backyard.

### Recent Political Role
In 2025, he joined the Department of Government Efficiency (DOGE). Gebbia was appointed by President Donald Trump as the first Chief Design Officer to lead the National Design Studio.

### Philanthropy
In December 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic, Gebbia made a $25 million donation to benefit two San Francisco charities working to end homelessness in the San Francisco Bay Area: Rising UpLarkin Street Youth Services and All Home. In May 2022, while Gebbia was the graduation speaker at his alma mater, Brookwood High School, he pledged 22 shares of Airbnb stock to each of the 890 graduates, a gift worth a total of $2.1 million.

## Nathan Blecharczyk - Co-founder and Chief Strategy Officer

### Background and Early Life
Blecharczyk was born in 1983, the son of Sheila (ne Underwood) and Paul Steven Blecharczyk, who is Polish-American. His ancestors came to the United States around the time of World War I. He grew up in an upper-middle-class family in Boston, Massachusetts. He attended Boston Latin Academy, graduating in 2001.

### Early Entrepreneurship
During high school, he made money by creating a software business. His web-hosting business provided services to spammers and was once listed on The Spamhaus Project "Registry of Known Spam Operators (ROKSO)" which lists the top spamming services.

Lifelong entrepreneur, Nathan Blecharczyk started coding at the age of 12. At the age of 14, his first customer paid $1000 for his work he saw online. By the time he finished high school, he made over $1 million.

Blecharczyk, a then 19-year-old self-taught engineer, already raked in $1 million from the software business he developed in high school. From as young as 14, he started attracting clients from all over the world who sought his help in writing computer programs.

### Education and Career Development
But by the second year, it was becoming too much to try to balance that," Blecharczyk told FOX Business. Drawing on the confidence that his father instilled in him at a very young age, he shut down his business knowing "that there would be other opportunities in the future."

In 2005, he graduated with a bachelor's degree in computer science, which helped him not only build the technological underpinnings for Airbnb but negotiate with policymakers in communities around the world to enable the company's expansion.

### Role in Founding Airbnb
In February 2008, Nathan Blecharczyk, Chesky's former roommate, joined as the chief technology officer and the third co-founder of the new venture, which they named "AirBed & Breakfast". In 2008, Blecharczyk partnered with Brian Chesky and Joe Gebbia to found Airbnb, and was the company's first chief technology officer and coded the company's original website using Ruby on Rails.

### Current Role and Responsibilities
Nathan (Nate) Blecharczyk is the co-founder of Airbnb and Chief Strategy Officer. Nate plays a leading role in driving key strategic initiatives across the global business, particularly those which require a holistic understanding of the business, public policy, product, data, and Airbnb's long-term stakeholder interests. Nate has led the creation of Airbnb's engineering, data science, payments, and performance marketing teams.

In his role as chief strategy officer, Blecharczyk is in charge of making nice with local governments within the U.S. and around the world and convincing landlords to let the tenants rent their rooms on Airbnb. "I take a very long-term view that it's important to have positive relations with regulators and create value for the stakeholders," he says.

### Personal Life and Net Worth
Blecharczyk is the 203rd richest person in the world according to Forbes, with a net worth of $9.4 billion, mostly due to his ownership of 62 million shares of Airbnb. Blecharczyk resides in San Francisco, California. He is married to Elizabeth Morey Blecharczyk, a neonatologist. They have two children; Blecharczyk has been a supporter of parental leave for fathers.

Blecharczyk joined Warren Buffett and Bill Gates' 'The Giving Pledge', a select group of billionaires who have committed to give the majority of their wealth away.

## The Early Struggle and Creative Solutions

### The Cereal Box Innovation
During their early struggles to secure funding, the founders demonstrated remarkable creativity and perseverance. Later that year, after failing to raise funding, the founders bought mass quantities of cereal, designed packaging branded as '"Obama O's" and "Cap'n McCain's" cereal to sell at the Democratic National Convention in Denver, Colorado. Originally intended as a marketing ploy, the company sold enough cereal to raise $30,000, and attracted the attention of Paul Graham, who invited the founders to the January 2009 winter training session of his startup incubator, Y Combinator, which provided them with training and $20,000 in funding in exchange for a 6% interest in the company.

### Y Combinator and Growth
In early 2009, Chesky, Gebbia, and Blecharczyk enrolled in a Y Combinator startup course. The course provided US$20,000 in seed money and training from Paul Graham, among others, in exchange for a six-percent stake in the company. Sequoia Capital partner Greg McAdoo invested US$585,000 in what was now known as Airbnb at the end of the course.

## Company Evolution and Success

In December 2020, Airbnb became a public company via an initial public offering. Since then, Brian has overseen Airbnb's growth to become a community of over 5 million hosts who have welcomed more than 2 billion guests across 240+ countries and regions.

The three founders represent a unique combination of design thinking (Chesky and Gebbia from RISD) and technical expertise (Blecharczyk from Harvard), which proved essential in creating both a user-friendly platform and the underlying technology infrastructure. Their story demonstrates how complementary skills, creative problem-solving during difficult times, and long-term vision can transform a simple idea into a global business phenomenon.

---

**Sources:**
- Airbnb official newsroom and investor relations pages
- Wikipedia entries for all three founders
- Business publications including CNBC, Fox Business, Medium
- Interviews and profiles from various entrepreneurship publications

The early investors in Airbnb, particularly Y Combinator and Sequoia Capital, saw several compelling factors:

# Comprehensive Research: Airbnb Founders - Brian Chesky, Joe Gebbia, and Nathan Blecharczyk

## Overview

Airbnb was founded in 2008 by three entrepreneurs who transformed a simple idea born out of financial necessity into a global hospitality platform valued at over $100 billion. The three co-founders each brought unique backgrounds and skills that proved complementary in building one of the most successful startups of the 21st century.

## Brian Chesky - Co-founder and CEO

### Background and Early Life
Brian Joseph Chesky was born on August 29, 1981, in Niskayuna, New York. His parents are Robert H. Chesky and Deborah Chesky; they both were social workers. His father is of Polish ancestry, whereas his mother is of Italian descent. When Chesky was a child, he was interested in art, drawing, and design, and he often redesigned shoes and toys. Later, his interests shifted to landscape architecture and design.

### Education and Early Career
In 1999, Brian Chesky enrolled at the Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) and served as their hockey team captain. He completed his RISD program in 2004 and was awarded a Bachelor of Fine Arts in industrial design. While at RISD, Chesky met Joe Gebbia, who would later become his best friend, housemate, and one of Airbnb's co-founders.

In his early 20s, he also became a competitive bodybuilder, and a 2014 profile said he still had "16-inch biceps." After completing his RISD program, Brian Chesky relocated to Los Angeles. Subsequently, he found an industrial designer job that fetched $40,000 annually.

At age 22 he was overcome by a "weird feeling of mortality." A sense of "this is my life": Commuting in LA traffic alone to a job in a design company. It was a let down after he'd started to believe the high-minded rhetoric from Rhode Island School of Design that designers could "design the world around them." He quit that job, rolled up a foam bed into his crappy Honda Civic and moved in with his old design pal Joe Gebbia in San Francisco.

### Founding Airbnb
In October 2007, he moved to San Francisco to live with RISD classmate Joe Gebbia. Chesky did not have enough money to pay his rent, and they opened their house to short-term renters as a bed and breakfast, providing air mattresses for guests to sleep on and Pop-Tarts for breakfast during the Industrial Designers Society of America conference, when hotel rooms were scarce. The business became Airbnb.

### Leadership Style and Philosophy
Brian Chesky is the co-founder and Chief Executive Officer of Airbnb and sets the vision and strategy for the company. A graduate from the Rhode Island School of Design, Brian has embedded his creative roots in Airbnb's culture, product and community. This design-driven approach has enabled a system of trust that allows strangers to live together, and created a unique business model that facilitates connection and belonging.

In September 2024, Chesky gave a 2-hour talk at a Y Combinator event on his leadership style, later coined "founder mode" by American computer scientist Paul Graham in an essay. Chesky's talk garnered attention quickly and became the subject of widespread discussion and memes.

### Current Status and Philanthropy
As of May 2023, Airbnb's market capitalization is $74.9 billion, and its 42-year-old CEO has a real-time net worth estimated at $9.3 billion. On June 11, 2016, Chesky joined Warren Buffett and Bill Gates' The Giving Pledge, a group of billionaires who have committed to giving the majority of their wealth away.

## Joe Gebbia - Co-founder

### Background and Early Life
Gebbia was born August 21, 1981, in Atlanta, Georgia, the son of Eileen and Joe Gebbia, independent health food sales representatives. Gebbia is of Italian and Irish ancestry. He grew up in Lawrenceville, Georgia and has one sister, Kimberly. Gebbia attended Brookwood High School in Snellville, Georgia.

### Education and Artistic Background
Joe began his life as an artist and graduated from the Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) where he earned dual degrees in Graphic Design and Industrial Design, and currently serves on the RISD Board of Trustees. Most people don't know that Joe began his life as an artist eventually double majoring in graphic design and industrial design.

### Role in Founding Airbnb
In 2007, Brian Chesky, his classmate at RISD, moved in with him, and they both quit their jobs to start a company together. Gebbia came up with the idea of renting out airbeds in their apartment. As a result, Gebbia wrote Chesky with an idea: What if they turned their loft into a designer's bed and breakfast, with a sleeping mat and breakfast included? They opted to welcome some conference attendees in their room right away as a way of "making some bucks." They bought three airbeds and hosted three guests, effectively initiating the bed and breakfast business.

### Career Evolution and Current Roles
In July 2022, Gebbia stepped down from his full-time operating role at Airbnb, while remaining on the board of directors in an advisory role. In September 2022, Gebbia was appointed by Tesla, Inc. to its board of directors.

Samara, formerly a research and development unit of Airbnb established in 2016, became an independent accessory dwelling unit (ADU) startup in 2022. Gebbia announced the launch of its first product in November 2022, a net-zero tiny house called Backyard.

### Recent Political Role
In 2025, he joined the Department of Government Efficiency (DOGE). Gebbia was appointed by President Donald Trump as the first Chief Design Officer to lead the National Design Studio.

### Philanthropy
In December 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic, Gebbia made a $25 million donation to benefit two San Francisco charities working to end homelessness in the San Francisco Bay Area: Rising UpLarkin Street Youth Services and All Home. In May 2022, while Gebbia was the graduation speaker at his alma mater, Brookwood High School, he pledged 22 shares of Airbnb stock to each of the 890 graduates, a gift worth a total of $2.1 million.

## Nathan Blecharczyk - Co-founder and Chief Strategy Officer

### Background and Early Life
Blecharczyk was born in 1983, the son of Sheila (ne Underwood) and Paul Steven Blecharczyk, who is Polish-American. His ancestors came to the United States around the time of World War I. He grew up in an upper-middle-class family in Boston, Massachusetts. He attended Boston Latin Academy, graduating in 2001.

### Early Entrepreneurship
During high school, he made money by creating a software business. His web-hosting business provided services to spammers and was once listed on The Spamhaus Project "Registry of Known Spam Operators (ROKSO)" which lists the top spamming services.

Lifelong entrepreneur, Nathan Blecharczyk started coding at the age of 12. At the age of 14, his first customer paid $1000 for his work he saw online. By the time he finished high school, he made over $1 million.

Blecharczyk, a then 19-year-old self-taught engineer, already raked in $1 million from the software business he developed in high school. From as young as 14, he started attracting clients from all over the world who sought his help in writing computer programs.

### Education and Career Development
But by the second year, it was becoming too much to try to balance that," Blecharczyk told FOX Business. Drawing on the confidence that his father instilled in him at a very young age, he shut down his business knowing "that there would be other opportunities in the future."

In 2005, he graduated with a bachelor's degree in computer science, which helped him not only build the technological underpinnings for Airbnb but negotiate with policymakers in communities around the world to enable the company's expansion.

### Role in Founding Airbnb
In February 2008, Nathan Blecharczyk, Chesky's former roommate, joined as the chief technology officer and the third co-founder of the new venture, which they named "AirBed & Breakfast". In 2008, Blecharczyk partnered with Brian Chesky and Joe Gebbia to found Airbnb, and was the company's first chief technology officer and coded the company's original website using Ruby on Rails.

### Current Role and Responsibilities
Nathan (Nate) Blecharczyk is the co-founder of Airbnb and Chief Strategy Officer. Nate plays a leading role in driving key strategic initiatives across the global business, particularly those which require a holistic understanding of the business, public policy, product, data, and Airbnb's long-term stakeholder interests. Nate has led the creation of Airbnb's engineering, data science, payments, and performance marketing teams.

In his role as chief strategy officer, Blecharczyk is in charge of making nice with local governments within the U.S. and around the world and convincing landlords to let the tenants rent their rooms on Airbnb. "I take a very long-term view that it's important to have positive relations with regulators and create value for the stakeholders," he says.

### Personal Life and Net Worth
Blecharczyk is the 203rd richest person in the world according to Forbes, with a net worth of $9.4 billion, mostly due to his ownership of 62 million shares of Airbnb. Blecharczyk resides in San Francisco, California. He is married to Elizabeth Morey Blecharczyk, a neonatologist. They have two children; Blecharczyk has been a supporter of parental leave for fathers.

Blecharczyk joined Warren Buffett and Bill Gates' 'The Giving Pledge', a select group of billionaires who have committed to give the majority of their wealth away.

## The Early Struggle and Creative Solutions

### The Cereal Box Innovation
During their early struggles to secure funding, the founders demonstrated remarkable creativity and perseverance. Later that year, after failing to raise funding, the founders bought mass quantities of cereal, designed packaging branded as '"Obama O's" and "Cap'n McCain's" cereal to sell at the Democratic National Convention in Denver, Colorado. Originally intended as a marketing ploy, the company sold enough cereal to raise $30,000, and attracted the attention of Paul Graham, who invited the founders to the January 2009 winter training session of his startup incubator, Y Combinator, which provided them with training and $20,000 in funding in exchange for a 6% interest in the company.

### Y Combinator and Growth
In early 2009, Chesky, Gebbia, and Blecharczyk enrolled in a Y Combinator startup course. The course provided US$20,000 in seed money and training from Paul Graham, among others, in exchange for a six-percent stake in the company. Sequoia Capital partner Greg McAdoo invested US$585,000 in what was now known as Airbnb at the end of the course.

## Company Evolution and Success

In December 2020, Airbnb became a public company via an initial public offering. Since then, Brian has overseen Airbnb's growth to become a community of over 5 million hosts who have welcomed more than 2 billion guests across 240+ countries and regions.

The three founders represent a unique combination of design thinking (Chesky and Gebbia from RISD) and technical expertise (Blecharczyk from Harvard), which proved essential in creating both a user-friendly platform and the underlying technology infrastructure. Their story demonstrates how complementary skills, creative problem-solving during difficult times, and long-term vision can transform a simple idea into a global business phenomenon.

---

**Sources:**
- Airbnb official newsroom and investor relations pages
- Wikipedia entries for all three founders
- Business publications including CNBC, Fox Business, Medium
- Interviews and profiles from various entrepreneurship publications

## Overview
Airbnb was founded in 2008 by three entrepreneurs who transformed a simple idea born from financial necessity into a global hospitality platform valued at over $100 billion.

### Brian Chesky - Co-founder and CEO
- **Born:** August 29, 1981, in Niskayuna, New York

### Joe Gebbia - Co-founder
- **Born:** August 21, 1981, in Atlanta, Georgia

  - Airbnb Board Member (stepped down from operations in July 2022)

### Nathan Blecharczyk - Co-founder and Chief Strategy Officer

- **Education:** Bachelor's degree in Computer Science from Harvard University, 2005
- **Current Role:** Chief Strategy Officer at Airbnb
- **Net Worth:** ~$9.4 billion (Forbes)
- **Key Facts:**
  - Started coding at age 12
  - Made over $1 million from software business by high school graduation
  - Built Airbnb's original website
  - Leads strategic initiatives and government relations

## The Founding Story

### The Beginning (2007-2008)
- October 2007: Brian Chesky moved in with Joe Gebbia in San Francisco
- Both were struggling to pay rent
- During an Industrial Designers Society conference, they rented out air mattresses in their apartment
- February 2008: Nathan Blecharczyk joined as CTO

### Creative Funding Solutions
- Failed to secure initial funding
- Created "Obama O's" and "Cap'n McCain's" cereal boxes during 2008 Democratic National Convention
- Raised $30,000 from cereal sales
- Caught attention of Y Combinator's Paul Graham

### Y Combinator and Growth
- January 2009: Accepted into Y Combinator
- Received $20,000 for 6% equity
- Sequoia Capital invested $585,000 after the program

## Investment Rationale

### Early Stage Investment Thesis
The early investors in Airbnb, particularly Y Combinator and Sequoia Capital, saw several compelling factors:

**1. Founder Characteristics**
- **Resourcefulness:** The cereal box fundraising demonstrated exceptional creativity and hustle
- **Complementary Skills:** Design expertise (Chesky/Gebbia) + technical prowess (Blecharczyk)
- **Persistence:** Continued despite multiple rejections and near-bankruptcy

**2. Market Opportunity**
- **Untapped Supply:** Millions of unused rooms and properties worldwide
- **Price Arbitrage:** Significant gap between hotel prices and potential home-sharing rates
- **Global Scalability:** Model could work in any city with housing and tourism

**3. Network Effects**
- **Two-sided Marketplace:** More hosts attract more guests, and vice versa
- **Trust System:** Reviews create self-reinforcing quality control
- **Geographic Density:** Success in one area makes expansion to nearby areas easier

### Key Investment Milestones
- **2009:** Sequoia Capital - $585,000 (seed)
- **2010:** Series A - $7.2 million (Greylock Partners led)
- **2011:** Series B - $112 million (Andreessen Horowitz led, $1 billion valuation)
- **2020:** IPO at $68/share, reaching $130 on first day (91% gain)

### Why Investors Believed
- **Capital Efficiency:** Asset-light model with no real estate ownership
- **Defensibility:** Strong brand and two-sided network effects
- **TAM Expansion:** Started with budget travelers, expanded to luxury and business travel
- **Platform Potential:** Could expand beyond accommodations (Experiences, long-term stays)

### Return on Investment
- Y Combinator's $20,000 for 6% became worth ~$4.5 billion at IPO
- Sequoia's early investments returned over 1,000x
- Demonstrated one of the best venture capital returns in history

## Company Success
- December 2020: Went public via IPO
- Current market cap: ~$74.9 billion
- Over 5 million hosts worldwide
- More than 2 billion guests served across 240+ countries

## Key Success Factors
The founders' complementary skills proved essential:
- **Design thinking:** Chesky and Gebbia (RISD background)
- **Technical expertise:** Blecharczyk (Harvard CS background)
- **Creative problem-solving:** Demonstrated through cereal box fundraising
- **Long-term vision:** Transform hospitality industry through trust and belonging

result.note:
# Airbnb Founders: Background and Founding Story Research

## The Three Founders

### Brian Chesky - CEO and Co-founder

**Background:**
Brian Joseph Chesky was born on August 29, 1981, in Niskayuna, New York, the son of Deborah and Robert Chesky. Chesky's parents were both social workers, and his father is of Polish and his mother of French origin. As a child, Chesky's first hobby was ice hockey. He developed an interest in art in his teens and cited Leonardo da Vinci as an early inspiration. He drew replicas of paintings and redesigned toys and shoes.

**Education and Early Career:**
He graduated from the Rhode Island School of Design with a degree in industrial design. Prior to founding Airbnb, Chesky worked as a designer at a number of startups and also founded a design firm. Before Airbnb, he worked as an industrial designer and founded Brian Chesky Design. Chesky had just left a job on the Simon Cowell show American Inventor in Los Angeles before moving to San Francisco.

### Joe Gebbia - Co-founder and Former CPO

**Background:**
Joseph Gebbia Jr. was born August 21, 1981, in Atlanta, Georgia, the son of Eileen and Joe Gebbia, independent health food sales representatives. Gebbia is of Italian and Irish ancestry. He grew up in Lawrenceville, Georgia and has one sister, Kimberly.

**Education and Early Ventures:**
In 2005, Gebbia graduated from the Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) with a Bachelor of Fine Arts degree in Graphic Design and Industrial Design. Gebbia took supplementary business-related classes at Brown University and Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) while attending RISD. 

Before Airbnb, he also founded Ecolect, a green-design website. At the time, Gebbia was creating two different ventures, one designing cushions for back sufferers and another building a website for product designers to find eco-friendly resources. He notably created CritBunssoft, foamy pillows that were intended to cushion (and keep clean) the bums of art students as they sat on hard stools and dirty floors during hours-long critique sessions, which he got on the shelves of the Museum of Modern Art's prestigious design store in New York.

### Nathan Blecharczyk - Co-founder and Chief Strategy Officer

**Background:**
He grew up in an upper-middle-class family in Boston, Massachusetts. He attended Boston Latin Academy, graduating in 2001. During high school, he made money by creating a software business. In fact, he was able to fund his way through school from the money he gardened through an internet software business he founded at 14 years old.

**Education and Technical Background:**
Blecharczyk holds a degree in computer science from Harvard University and has worked as a software engineer at Microsoft and a number of startups before founding Airbnb. The 29-year old, and quietest one amongst the trio, had graduated Harvard with a degree in computer science in 2005. He was known as a 'brilliant programmer'.

## The Founding Story

### The Original Idea (2007)

In October 2007, he moved to San Francisco to live with RISD classmate Joe Gebbia. In 2007 Brian Chesky and Joe Gebbia were broke and looking to raise money to make their rent in San Francisco. They decided to rent out air mattresses in their apartment to attendees of a conference because all the hotels were booked.

Gebbia wrote Chesky with an idea: What if they turned their loft into a designer's bed and breakfast, with a sleeping mat and breakfast included? They opted to welcome some conference attendees in their room right away as a way of "making some bucks." They bought three airbeds and hosted three guests, effectively initiating the bed and breakfast business. Each guest paid $80 to spend the night on an air mattress.

### Bringing in the Third Founder

They invited Nathan Blecharczyk, one of Joe's old roommates and brilliant developer, to join them and to create a website for their idea. Gebbia and Chesky asked Nathan Blecharczyk to work on a new website for the company, then known as Airbed & Breakfast. They called it 'Air Bed and Breakfast' then. The three co-founders, Brian Chesky, Joe Gebbia, and Nathan Blecharczyk went on to launch their website named Airbedandbreakfast.com.

### Early Struggles - "The Trough of Sorrows"

The "Trough of Sorrows" was the name given to this portion of the Airbnb company story by Airbnb founder Brian Chesky. One instance occurred during the SXSW 2008 Conference, when the website only received two bookings, one of which was Chesky himself. Second, after learning from past mistakes that a lack of rooms led to people looking for other places to stay, the team tried again for the 2008 Democratic National Convention in Denver, with disastrous effects. While the team was able to gain media exposure, they were unable to gain user traction.

### The Famous Cereal Box Solution (2008)

Facing near-bankruptcy, the founders came up with one of startup history's most creative fundraising ideas. Chesky and Gebbia created presidential-themed breakfast cereals - The Obama O's - Barack Obama and "Cap'N McCains" John McCain cereal to capitalize on election fever. Each limited-edition cereal box sold for $40, and the founders numbered and handcrafted each box.

They made use of their designer skills to develop custom-designed Obama and McCain-themed cereal boxes with the catchy titles of "Obama O's: The Breakfast of Change" and "Capn' McCains: A Maverick in Every Bite." After securing hundreds of printed boxes from a Rhode Island School of Design connection, they bought the cheapest cereal in the market and filled up shopping carts. Back in their apartment, they hand-folded the boxes and sealed them with a hot-glue gun. By pitching the product as a limited-edition collector item, they sold them for $40 a box.

Weirdly enough, they ended up selling $30,000 of cereal. And that's how they remained afloat. The company sold out of boxes and even saw celebrities like Perez Hilton and Katy Perry buy the product.

### Y Combinator Acceptance

The cereal story became crucial to their acceptance into Y Combinator. In November 2008, Y Combinator founder Paul Graham was skeptical about Airbnb's business model. However, through the presidential-themed cereal boxes, Paul was won over by the founders' spirit and passion.

Tech startup accelerator Y Combinator co-founder Paul Graham offered them an investment specifically because of the cereal. "If you can convince people to pay $40 for $4 boxes of cereal, maybe, just maybe, you can convince strangers to live with each other," Graham told the trio.

"On the ride home, we get a phone call from Paul Graham to inform us that he'd like to offer us a spot in the Y Combinator program, and we later found out that the reason wasn't because of our idea," said Gebbia. "It was because through the breakfast cereal we had proven to him that we had hustle, that we had grit. If we could figure out how to sell breakfast cereal for 40 dollars a box, we could figure out how to make our website work."

### Early Funding and Growth

In early 2009, Chesky, Gebbia, and Blecharczyk enrolled in a Y Combinator startup course. The course provided US$20,000 in seed money and training from Paul Graham, among others, in exchange for a six-percent stake in the company. Sequoia Capital partner Greg McAdoo invested US$585,000 in what was now known as Airbnb at the end of the course.

They are still making only $200 a week and decide to use the money to travel to New York, their biggest market, to meet their users. They discover that the main problem is that the pictures of most listings aren't good. They buy a camera and go door-to-door to take better pictures of the listings.

## Key Characteristics and Lessons

The whole story around their origin takes a lot more twists and turns than most people know. They've oversimplified it to tell the story hundreds of times, but it really was purely accidental  as are many of the most interesting kinds of inventions. Everyone thought that they were completely crazy; no one thought this was a good idea.

The fewer resources you have, the more creative you become. There is no overnight success. Even for Airbnb, it took them over a year to secure investor funding.

The founding story exemplifies resilience, creativity, and the willingness to do unconventional things to survive. The cereal campaign became legendary in Silicon Valley as an example of "doing things that don't scale" and the hustle required in early-stage startups.

Today, with over 2 million guests per night, 100,000 listed cities, and a $26 billion valuation, it's fair to say the co-founders won't be piling up credit card debt any time soon, though the company went public in 2020 at an even higher valuation.

# Airbnb Founders: Brian Chesky, Joe Gebbia, and Nathan Blecharczyk

## The Three Co-Founders

### Brian Chesky - CEO and Co-founder
- **Born:** August 29, 1981, in Niskayuna, New York
- **Background:** Son of social workers (Deborah and Robert Chesky), with Polish and French heritage
- **Education:** Rhode Island School of Design (RISD), degree in Industrial Design
- **Early Career:** Worked as an industrial designer, founded Brian Chesky Design, and worked on American Inventor show in Los Angeles
- **Early Interests:** Ice hockey as a child, later developed passion for art inspired by Leonardo da Vinci

### Joe Gebbia - Co-founder and Former CPO
- **Born:** August 21, 1981, in Atlanta, Georgia
- **Background:** Son of independent health food sales representatives (Eileen and Joe Gebbia), Italian and Irish ancestry
- **Education:** RISD (2005), Bachelor of Fine Arts in Graphic Design and Industrial Design, with supplementary business classes at Brown and MIT
- **Early Ventures:** Founded Ecolect (green-design website) and created CritBuns (cushions for art students) sold at MoMA's design store

### Nathan Blecharczyk - Co-founder and Chief Strategy Officer
- **Background:** Grew up in upper-middle-class Boston family
- **Education:** Boston Latin Academy (2001), Harvard University degree in Computer Science (2005)
- **Early Career:** Founded an internet software business at age 14, worked as software engineer at Microsoft
- **Known as:** The "brilliant programmer" and quietest member of the founding trio

## The Founding Story

### The Beginning (October 2007)
Brian Chesky moved to San Francisco to live with his RISD classmate Joe Gebbia. Both were broke and struggling to make rent. When a design conference came to town and all hotels were booked, they had an idea: rent out air mattresses in their apartment with breakfast included. They hosted three guests at $80 per night, launching what would become Airbnb.

### Building the Team
Chesky and Gebbia invited Nathan Blecharczyk, Joe's former roommate and talented developer, to join them and create a website. They launched Airbedandbreakfast.com together.

### The "Trough of Sorrows" (2008)

- **Obama O's: The Breakfast of Change**
- **Cap'N McCains: A Maverick in Every Bite**

- Attracted celebrity buyers (Perez Hilton, Katy Perry)

### Y Combinator Breakthrough (Late 2008)
Paul Graham initially skeptical of Airbnb's business model, but the cereal story changed his mind. He famously said: "If you can convince people to pay $40 for $4 boxes of cereal, maybe you can convince strangers to live with each other."

The founders:
- Accepted into Y Combinator (early 2009)
- Received $20,000 seed funding
- Gave up 6% equity
- Later secured $585,000 from Sequoia Capital's Greg McAdoo

Making only $200/week, the founders traveled to New York (their biggest market) and discovered poor listing photos were hurting bookings. They bought a camera and went door-to-door taking professional photos of listings - an example of "doing things that don't scale."

From three air mattresses in a San Francisco apartment, Airbnb has grown to:

result.note:
# Airbnb Founders: Background and Founding Story Research

## The Three Founders

### Brian Chesky - CEO and Co-founder

**Background:**
Brian Joseph Chesky was born on August 29, 1981, in Niskayuna, New York, the son of Deborah and Robert Chesky. Chesky's parents were both social workers, and his father is of Polish and his mother of French origin. As a child, Chesky's first hobby was ice hockey. He developed an interest in art in his teens and cited Leonardo da Vinci as an early inspiration. He drew replicas of paintings and redesigned toys and shoes.

**Education and Early Career:**
He graduated from the Rhode Island School of Design with a degree in industrial design. Prior to founding Airbnb, Chesky worked as a designer at a number of startups and also founded a design firm. Before Airbnb, he worked as an industrial designer and founded Brian Chesky Design. Chesky had just left a job on the Simon Cowell show American Inventor in Los Angeles before moving to San Francisco.

### Joe Gebbia - Co-founder and Former CPO

**Background:**
Joseph Gebbia Jr. was born August 21, 1981, in Atlanta, Georgia, the son of Eileen and Joe Gebbia, independent health food sales representatives. Gebbia is of Italian and Irish ancestry. He grew up in Lawrenceville, Georgia and has one sister, Kimberly.

**Education and Early Ventures:**
In 2005, Gebbia graduated from the Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) with a Bachelor of Fine Arts degree in Graphic Design and Industrial Design. Gebbia took supplementary business-related classes at Brown University and Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) while attending RISD. 

Before Airbnb, he also founded Ecolect, a green-design website. At the time, Gebbia was creating two different ventures, one designing cushions for back sufferers and another building a website for product designers to find eco-friendly resources. He notably created CritBunssoft, foamy pillows that were intended to cushion (and keep clean) the bums of art students as they sat on hard stools and dirty floors during hours-long critique sessions, which he got on the shelves of the Museum of Modern Art's prestigious design store in New York.

### Nathan Blecharczyk - Co-founder and Chief Strategy Officer

**Background:**
He grew up in an upper-middle-class family in Boston, Massachusetts. He attended Boston Latin Academy, graduating in 2001. During high school, he made money by creating a software business. In fact, he was able to fund his way through school from the money he gardened through an internet software business he founded at 14 years old.

**Education and Technical Background:**
Blecharczyk holds a degree in computer science from Harvard University and has worked as a software engineer at Microsoft and a number of startups before founding Airbnb. The 29-year old, and quietest one amongst the trio, had graduated Harvard with a degree in computer science in 2005. He was known as a 'brilliant programmer'.

## The Founding Story

### The Original Idea (2007)

In October 2007, he moved to San Francisco to live with RISD classmate Joe Gebbia. In 2007 Brian Chesky and Joe Gebbia were broke and looking to raise money to make their rent in San Francisco. They decided to rent out air mattresses in their apartment to attendees of a conference because all the hotels were booked.

Gebbia wrote Chesky with an idea: What if they turned their loft into a designer's bed and breakfast, with a sleeping mat and breakfast included? They opted to welcome some conference attendees in their room right away as a way of "making some bucks." They bought three airbeds and hosted three guests, effectively initiating the bed and breakfast business. Each guest paid $80 to spend the night on an air mattress.

### Bringing in the Third Founder

They invited Nathan Blecharczyk, one of Joe's old roommates and brilliant developer, to join them and to create a website for their idea. Gebbia and Chesky asked Nathan Blecharczyk to work on a new website for the company, then known as Airbed & Breakfast. They called it 'Air Bed and Breakfast' then. The three co-founders, Brian Chesky, Joe Gebbia, and Nathan Blecharczyk went on to launch their website named Airbedandbreakfast.com.

### Early Struggles - "The Trough of Sorrows"

The "Trough of Sorrows" was the name given to this portion of the Airbnb company story by Airbnb founder Brian Chesky. One instance occurred during the SXSW 2008 Conference, when the website only received two bookings, one of which was Chesky himself. Second, after learning from past mistakes that a lack of rooms led to people looking for other places to stay, the team tried again for the 2008 Democratic National Convention in Denver, with disastrous effects. While the team was able to gain media exposure, they were unable to gain user traction.

### The Famous Cereal Box Solution (2008)

Facing near-bankruptcy, the founders came up with one of startup history's most creative fundraising ideas. Chesky and Gebbia created presidential-themed breakfast cereals - The Obama O's - Barack Obama and "Cap'N McCains" John McCain cereal to capitalize on election fever. Each limited-edition cereal box sold for $40, and the founders numbered and handcrafted each box.

They made use of their designer skills to develop custom-designed Obama and McCain-themed cereal boxes with the catchy titles of "Obama O's: The Breakfast of Change" and "Capn' McCains: A Maverick in Every Bite." After securing hundreds of printed boxes from a Rhode Island School of Design connection, they bought the cheapest cereal in the market and filled up shopping carts. Back in their apartment, they hand-folded the boxes and sealed them with a hot-glue gun. By pitching the product as a limited-edition collector item, they sold them for $40 a box.

Weirdly enough, they ended up selling $30,000 of cereal. And that's how they remained afloat. The company sold out of boxes and even saw celebrities like Perez Hilton and Katy Perry buy the product.

### Y Combinator Acceptance

The cereal story became crucial to their acceptance into Y Combinator. In November 2008, Y Combinator founder Paul Graham was skeptical about Airbnb's business model. However, through the presidential-themed cereal boxes, Paul was won over by the founders' spirit and passion.

Tech startup accelerator Y Combinator co-founder Paul Graham offered them an investment specifically because of the cereal. "If you can convince people to pay $40 for $4 boxes of cereal, maybe, just maybe, you can convince strangers to live with each other," Graham told the trio.

"On the ride home, we get a phone call from Paul Graham to inform us that he'd like to offer us a spot in the Y Combinator program, and we later found out that the reason wasn't because of our idea," said Gebbia. "It was because through the breakfast cereal we had proven to him that we had hustle, that we had grit. If we could figure out how to sell breakfast cereal for 40 dollars a box, we could figure out how to make our website work."

### Early Funding and Growth

In early 2009, Chesky, Gebbia, and Blecharczyk enrolled in a Y Combinator startup course. The course provided US$20,000 in seed money and training from Paul Graham, among others, in exchange for a six-percent stake in the company. Sequoia Capital partner Greg McAdoo invested US$585,000 in what was now known as Airbnb at the end of the course.

They are still making only $200 a week and decide to use the money to travel to New York, their biggest market, to meet their users. They discover that the main problem is that the pictures of most listings aren't good. They buy a camera and go door-to-door to take better pictures of the listings.

## Key Characteristics and Lessons

The whole story around their origin takes a lot more twists and turns than most people know. They've oversimplified it to tell the story hundreds of times, but it really was purely accidental  as are many of the most interesting kinds of inventions. Everyone thought that they were completely crazy; no one thought this was a good idea.

The fewer resources you have, the more creative you become. There is no overnight success. Even for Airbnb, it took them over a year to secure investor funding.

The founding story exemplifies resilience, creativity, and the willingness to do unconventional things to survive. The cereal campaign became legendary in Silicon Valley as an example of "doing things that don't scale" and the hustle required in early-stage startups.

Today, with over 2 million guests per night, 100,000 listed cities, and a $26 billion valuation, it's fair to say the co-founders won't be piling up credit card debt any time soon, though the company went public in 2020 at an even higher valuation.

- **Born:** August 21, 1981, in Atlanta, Georgia
- **Background:** Son of independent health food sales representatives (Eileen and Joe Gebbia), Italian and Irish ancestry
- **Education:** RISD (2005), Bachelor of Fine Arts in Graphic Design and Industrial Design, with supplementary business classes at Brown and MIT
- **Early Ventures:** Founded Ecolect (green-design website) and created CritBuns (cushions for art students) sold at MoMA's design store

### Nathan Blecharczyk - Co-founder and Chief Strategy Officer
- **Background:** Grew up in upper-middle-class Boston family
- **Education:** Boston Latin Academy (2001), Harvard University degree in Computer Science (2005)
- **Early Career:** Founded an internet software business at age 14, worked as software engineer at Microsoft
- **Known as:** The "brilliant programmer" and quietest member of the founding trio

## The Founding Story

### The Beginning (October 2007)
Brian Chesky moved to San Francisco to live with his RISD classmate Joe Gebbia. Both were broke and struggling to make rent. When a design conference came to town and all hotels were booked, they had an idea: rent out air mattresses in their apartment with breakfast included. They hosted three guests at $80 per night, launching what would become Airbnb.

### Building the Team
Chesky and Gebbia invited Nathan Blecharczyk, Joe's former roommate and talented developer, to join them and create a website. They launched Airbedandbreakfast.com together.

### The "Trough of Sorrows" (2008)
The founders faced numerous challenges:
- SXSW 2008: Only 2 bookings (one was Chesky himself)
- Democratic National Convention 2008: Despite media exposure, failed to gain user traction
- Near bankruptcy with maxed-out credit cards

### The Famous Cereal Box Solution (2008)
Facing financial ruin, the founders created presidential-themed breakfast cereals:
- **Obama O's: The Breakfast of Change**
- **Cap'N McCains: A Maverick in Every Bite**

They hand-crafted and numbered each box, selling them as limited-edition collectibles for $40 each (containing $4 worth of cereal). The campaign:
- Raised $30,000
- Attracted celebrity buyers (Perez Hilton, Katy Perry)
- Demonstrated their hustle and creativity

### Y Combinator Breakthrough (Late 2008)
Paul Graham initially skeptical of Airbnb's business model, but the cereal story changed his mind. He famously said: "If you can convince people to pay $40 for $4 boxes of cereal, maybe you can convince strangers to live with each other."

The founders:
- Accepted into Y Combinator (early 2009)
- Received $20,000 seed funding
- Gave up 6% equity
- Later secured $585,000 from Sequoia Capital's Greg McAdoo

### Early Growth Tactics
Making only $200/week, the founders traveled to New York (their biggest market) and discovered poor listing photos were hurting bookings. They bought a camera and went door-to-door taking professional photos of listings - an example of "doing things that don't scale."

## Key Lessons from Their Journey
- **Creativity from constraints:** Limited resources forced innovative solutions
- **No overnight success:** Took over a year to secure investor funding
- **Hustle matters:** The cereal campaign became legendary in Silicon Valley
- **User focus:** Personally visiting users and improving their experience
- **Persistence:** Surviving the "Trough of Sorrows" through determination

## Today's Impact
From three air mattresses in a San Francisco apartment, Airbnb has grown to:
- Over 2 million guests per night
- 100,000+ listed cities
- IPO in 2020 with multi-billion dollar valuation

The founding story exemplifies how accidental beginnings, combined with resilience and creativity, can transform a simple idea into a global phenomenon.

### Brian Chesky - CEO and Co-founder

- **Background:** Son of social workers (Deborah and Robert Chesky), with Polish and French heritage
- **Education:** Rhode Island School of Design (RISD), degree in Industrial Design

- **Early Career:** Founded an internet software business at age 14, worked as software engineer at Microsoft
- **Known as:** The "brilliant programmer" and quietest member of the founding trio

## The Founding Story

### The Beginning (October 2007)
Brian Chesky moved to San Francisco to live with his RISD classmate Joe Gebbia. Both were broke and struggling to make rent. When a design conference came to town and all hotels were booked, they had an idea: rent out air mattresses in their apartment with breakfast included. They hosted three guests at $80 per night, launching what would become Airbnb.

### Building the Team
Chesky and Gebbia invited Nathan Blecharczyk, Joe's former roommate and talented developer, to join them and create a website. They launched Airbedandbreakfast.com together.

### The "Trough of Sorrows" (2008)
The founders faced numerous challenges:
- SXSW 2008: Only 2 bookings (one was Chesky himself)
- Democratic National Convention 2008: Despite media exposure, failed to gain user traction
- Near bankruptcy with maxed-out credit cards

### The Famous Cereal Box Solution (2008)
Facing financial ruin, the founders created presidential-themed breakfast cereals:
- **Obama O's: The Breakfast of Change**
- **Cap'N McCains: A Maverick in Every Bite**

They hand-crafted and numbered each box, selling them as limited-edition collectibles for $40 each (containing $4 worth of cereal). The campaign:
- Raised $30,000
- Attracted celebrity buyers (Perez Hilton, Katy Perry)

Paul Graham initially skeptical of Airbnb's business model, but the cereal story changed his mind. He famously said: "If you can convince people to pay $40 for $4 boxes of cereal, maybe you can convince strangers to live with each other."

- Accepted into Y Combinator (early 2009)
- Received $20,000 seed funding
- Gave up 6% equity

### Early Growth Tactics
Making only $200/week, the founders traveled to New York (their biggest market) and discovered poor listing photos were hurting bookings. They bought a camera and went door-to-door taking professional photos of listings - an example of "doing things that don't scale."

## Investment Rationale: Why VCs Bet on Airbnb

### Initial Skepticism Turned Belief
Early investors were highly skeptical of Airbnb's model. The idea of strangers staying in each other's homes seemed bizarre and potentially dangerous. However, several factors eventually convinced investors:

### Key Investment Drivers

**1. Founder Qualities**
- **Resilience:** The cereal box story demonstrated extraordinary hustle and refusal to give up
- **Customer Obsession:** Willingness to personally visit users and take photos showed deep commitment to user experience
- **Adaptability:** Ability to pivot and iterate based on market feedback

**2. Market Opportunity**
- **Massive TAM:** Global hotel industry worth hundreds of billions annually
- **Underutilized Assets:** Millions of empty rooms and properties worldwide
- **Price Advantage:** Typically 30-80% cheaper than comparable hotels
- **Unique Inventory:** Access to properties hotels could never offer (entire homes, unique spaces)

**3. Network Effects**
- **Two-sided Marketplace:** More hosts attract more guests, and vice versa
- **Geographic Density:** As listings increase in an area, the platform becomes more valuable
- **Trust and Reviews:** Rating system creates self-reinforcing quality control

**4. Capital Efficiency**
- **Asset-Light Model:** No real estate ownership or maintenance costs
- **Scalability:** Software platform could scale globally without proportional cost increases
- **High Margins:** Transaction-based revenue model with limited variable costs

**5. Cultural Shifts**
- **Experience Economy:** Travelers increasingly seeking authentic, local experiences
- **Sharing Economy:** Growing comfort with peer-to-peer transactions
- **Digital Natives:** Millennials more open to alternative accommodation

### Notable Early Investors and Their Thesis

**Y Combinator (2009)**
- Invested based on founder grit more than the idea itself
- Paul Graham's thesis: founders who could sell $40 cereal boxes could figure out anything

**Sequoia Capital (2009)**
- Greg McAdoo saw potential for global disruption of hospitality
- Believed in the founders' vision and execution ability
- $585,000 seed investment

**Greylock Partners (2011)**
- Reid Hoffman led $7.2M Series A
- Saw parallels to LinkedIn's network effects
- Believed in the "trust infrastructure" Airbnb was building

**Andreessen Horowitz (2011)**
- Participated in later rounds
- Marc Andreessen's thesis: "Software is eating the world" - including hospitality
- Saw Airbnb as a platform, not just a booking site

### The Contrarian Bet That Paid Off
Airbnb represented a classic contrarian investment:
- **What seemed crazy:** Strangers sleeping in each other's homes
- **What investors missed:** Human desire for connection, authenticity, and value
- **The outcome:** IPO at $47 billion valuation (2020), peak valuation over $130 billion

The investment rationale evolved from betting on exceptional founders to recognizing a fundamental shift in how people travel and connect globally.

## Key Lessons from Their Journey
- **Creativity from constraints:** Limited resources forced innovative solutions
- **No overnight success:** Took over a year to secure investor funding
- **Hustle matters:** The cereal campaign became legendary in Silicon Valley
- **User focus:** Personally visiting users and improving their experience
- **Persistence:** Surviving the "Trough of Sorrows" through determination

## Today's Impact
From three air mattresses in a San Francisco apartment, Airbnb has grown to:
- Over 2 million guests per night
- 100,000+ listed cities
- IPO in 2020 with multi-billion dollar valuation

The founding story exemplifies how accidental beginnings, combined with resilience and creativity, can transform a simple idea into a global phenomenon.

# Airbnb Founders: Background and Founding Story Research

## The Three Founders

### Brian Chesky - CEO and Co-founder

**Background:**
Brian Joseph Chesky was born on August 29, 1981, in Niskayuna, New York, the son of Deborah and Robert Chesky. Chesky's parents were both social workers, and his father is of Polish and his mother of French origin. As a child, Chesky's first hobby was ice hockey. He developed an interest in art in his teens and cited Leonardo da Vinci as an early inspiration. He drew replicas of paintings and redesigned toys and shoes.

**Education and Early Career:**
He graduated from the Rhode Island School of Design with a degree in industrial design. Prior to founding Airbnb, Chesky worked as a designer at a number of startups and also founded a design firm. Before Airbnb, he worked as an industrial designer and founded Brian Chesky Design. Chesky had just left a job on the Simon Cowell show American Inventor in Los Angeles before moving to San Francisco.

### Joe Gebbia - Co-founder and Former CPO

**Background:**
Joseph Gebbia Jr. was born August 21, 1981, in Atlanta, Georgia, the son of Eileen and Joe Gebbia, independent health food sales representatives. Gebbia is of Italian and Irish ancestry. He grew up in Lawrenceville, Georgia and has one sister, Kimberly.

**Education and Early Ventures:**
In 2005, Gebbia graduated from the Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) with a Bachelor of Fine Arts degree in Graphic Design and Industrial Design. Gebbia took supplementary business-related classes at Brown University and Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) while attending RISD. 

Before Airbnb, he also founded Ecolect, a green-design website. At the time, Gebbia was creating two different ventures, one designing cushions for back sufferers and another building a website for product designers to find eco-friendly resources. He notably created CritBunssoft, foamy pillows that were intended to cushion (and keep clean) the bums of art students as they sat on hard stools and dirty floors during hours-long critique sessions, which he got on the shelves of the Museum of Modern Art's prestigious design store in New York.

### Nathan Blecharczyk - Co-founder and Chief Strategy Officer

**Background:**
He grew up in an upper-middle-class family in Boston, Massachusetts. He attended Boston Latin Academy, graduating in 2001. During high school, he made money by creating a software business. In fact, he was able to fund his way through school from the money he gardened through an internet software business he founded at 14 years old.

**Education and Technical Background:**
Blecharczyk holds a degree in computer science from Harvard University and has worked as a software engineer at Microsoft and a number of startups before founding Airbnb. The 29-year old, and quietest one amongst the trio, had graduated Harvard with a degree in computer science in 2005. He was known as a 'brilliant programmer'.

## The Founding Story

### The Original Idea (2007)

In October 2007, he moved to San Francisco to live with RISD classmate Joe Gebbia. In 2007 Brian Chesky and Joe Gebbia were broke and looking to raise money to make their rent in San Francisco. They decided to rent out air mattresses in their apartment to attendees of a conference because all the hotels were booked.

Gebbia wrote Chesky with an idea: What if they turned their loft into a designer's bed and breakfast, with a sleeping mat and breakfast included? They opted to welcome some conference attendees in their room right away as a way of "making some bucks." They bought three airbeds and hosted three guests, effectively initiating the bed and breakfast business. Each guest paid $80 to spend the night on an air mattress.

### Bringing in the Third Founder

They invited Nathan Blecharczyk, one of Joe's old roommates and brilliant developer, to join them and to create a website for their idea. Gebbia and Chesky asked Nathan Blecharczyk to work on a new website for the company, then known as Airbed & Breakfast. They called it 'Air Bed and Breakfast' then. The three co-founders, Brian Chesky, Joe Gebbia, and Nathan Blecharczyk went on to launch their website named Airbedandbreakfast.com.

### Early Struggles - "The Trough of Sorrows"

The "Trough of Sorrows" was the name given to this portion of the Airbnb company story by Airbnb founder Brian Chesky. One instance occurred during the SXSW 2008 Conference, when the website only received two bookings, one of which was Chesky himself. Second, after learning from past mistakes that a lack of rooms led to people looking for other places to stay, the team tried again for the 2008 Democratic National Convention in Denver, with disastrous effects. While the team was able to gain media exposure, they were unable to gain user traction.

### The Famous Cereal Box Solution (2008)

Facing near-bankruptcy, the founders came up with one of startup history's most creative fundraising ideas. Chesky and Gebbia created presidential-themed breakfast cereals - The Obama O's - Barack Obama and "Cap'N McCains" John McCain cereal to capitalize on election fever. Each limited-edition cereal box sold for $40, and the founders numbered and handcrafted each box.

They made use of their designer skills to develop custom-designed Obama and McCain-themed cereal boxes with the catchy titles of "Obama O's: The Breakfast of Change" and "Capn' McCains: A Maverick in Every Bite." After securing hundreds of printed boxes from a Rhode Island School of Design connection, they bought the cheapest cereal in the market and filled up shopping carts. Back in their apartment, they hand-folded the boxes and sealed them with a hot-glue gun. By pitching the product as a limited-edition collector item, they sold them for $40 a box.

Weirdly enough, they ended up selling $30,000 of cereal. And that's how they remained afloat. The company sold out of boxes and even saw celebrities like Perez Hilton and Katy Perry buy the product.

### Y Combinator Acceptance

The cereal story became crucial to their acceptance into Y Combinator. In November 2008, Y Combinator founder Paul Graham was skeptical about Airbnb's business model. However, through the presidential-themed cereal boxes, Paul was won over by the founders' spirit and passion.

Tech startup accelerator Y Combinator co-founder Paul Graham offered them an investment specifically because of the cereal. "If you can convince people to pay $40 for $4 boxes of cereal, maybe, just maybe, you can convince strangers to live with each other," Graham told the trio.

"On the ride home, we get a phone call from Paul Graham to inform us that he'd like to offer us a spot in the Y Combinator program, and we later found out that the reason wasn't because of our idea," said Gebbia. "It was because through the breakfast cereal we had proven to him that we had hustle, that we had grit. If we could figure out how to sell breakfast cereal for 40 dollars a box, we could figure out how to make our website work."

### Early Funding and Growth

In early 2009, Chesky, Gebbia, and Blecharczyk enrolled in a Y Combinator startup course. The course provided US$20,000 in seed money and training from Paul Graham, among others, in exchange for a six-percent stake in the company. Sequoia Capital partner Greg McAdoo invested US$585,000 in what was now known as Airbnb at the end of the course.

They are still making only $200 a week and decide to use the money to travel to New York, their biggest market, to meet their users. They discover that the main problem is that the pictures of most listings aren't good. They buy a camera and go door-to-door to take better pictures of the listings.

## Key Characteristics and Lessons

The whole story around their origin takes a lot more twists and turns than most people know. They've oversimplified it to tell the story hundreds of times, but it really was purely accidental  as are many of the most interesting kinds of inventions. Everyone thought that they were completely crazy; no one thought this was a good idea.

The fewer resources you have, the more creative you become. There is no overnight success. Even for Airbnb, it took them over a year to secure investor funding.

The founding story exemplifies resilience, creativity, and the willingness to do unconventional things to survive. The cereal campaign became legendary in Silicon Valley as an example of "doing things that don't scale" and the hustle required in early-stage startups.

Today, with over 2 million guests per night, 100,000 listed cities, and a $26 billion valuation, it's fair to say the co-founders won't be piling up credit card debt any time soon, though the company went public in 2020 at an even higher valuation.
